
    Jim Acosta row: White House restores CNN reporter's pass

        

    
        
            Media playback is unsupported on your device
      
        
          
      
        Media captionTrump v AcostaThe White House has restored the press credentials of CNN reporter Jim Acosta, less than two weeks after withdrawing them over an argument with President Trump during a news conference.The reversal came days after a judge ordered the administration to reinstate the journalist's press pass.Announcing its decision on Monday, the White House also issued "rules governing future press conferences".These include allowing only a single question from each journalist.White House attacks CNN's Acosta lawsuit
The Acosta affair: An unpopular opinion
Follow-up questions, the White House adds in a letter to Mr Acosta, will only be allowed "at the discretion of the president or other White House officials".
    
        
The letter warned that further action against Acosta will be taken unless he follows the new rules.Mr Trump has threatened to walk out of future press briefings if reporters do not act with "decorum".Reacting to Monday's decision restoring his pass, Acosta said he was looking forward to returning to the White House.
    
        
